Here is a breakdown of how to make that magnetic selection and "drawing" mechanism work reliably without losing your mind to mechanical jamming:

1. The Magnetic Coupler Mechanics
To change a row's topology, your gantry moves a row of "active" drivers underneath the board, couples with the vertical columns via magnets, drives them to the new height, and uncouples.

The Holding Friction Problem: Because stepper motors lose all holding torque when unpowered, your 12-inch printed rectangular pillars will instantly slide back down due to gravity (and the weight of your D&D minis) the second the gantry uncouples and moves away.

The Solution (Passive Friction/Detents): You need the 12-inch pillars to stay exactly where the gantry leaves them. You can achieve this by adding physical friction or a passive mechanical hold to each column's guide channel:

Constant Friction Grippers: Line the guide slots with a high-friction material (like silicone or felt strips) that exerts just enough pressure to hold the weight of the pillar and a heavy mini, but can be easily overcome by the gantry's vertical motor.

Magnetic Detents: Embed small steel pins along the back of the 12-inch pillars at your standard "height step" intervals, with a stationary magnet on the frame. The pillar will naturally "click" and lock into discrete height levels.

2. The Multi-Pin Selection Carriage
Instead of just one magnet on the gantry that has to do every single square one by one (which would be incredibly slow), you can build a "Selector Bar" carriage that handles an entire row at once.

Permanent Magnets vs. Electromagnets: If you use permanent magnets on the gantry, the gantry has to physically move away (laterally) to break the magnetic bond after setting a pillar's height. If you use small 12V electromagnets on the carriage, you can simply turn the magnet off, drop the gantry down, and move to the next row instantly.

The NEMA 8 Trade-off: NEMA 8 motors are incredibly compact, but their torque is quite low. If you are lifting a 12-inch tall 3D-printed column plus overcoming the passive friction required to keep it from falling later, a tiny NEMA 8 might stall. Since they are only mounted on the moving gantry row now, you have more physical space—consider stepping up to NEMA 11 or NEMA 14 motors for the lifting carriage to get that extra torque margin.

3. The "Drawing" Routine & Gameplay Flow
Because the map takes time to "draw" itself row-by-row, you'll want to optimize the control sequence:

The Prep Phase: Before the game session or during a narrative break, the DM selects a new map layout in the software.

The Zeroing Pass: The gantry homes itself, moves to Row 1, engages the magnets, and pulls all pillars down to a baseline "zero" height.

The Step-Up Pass: The gantry sweeps row-by-row, engaging the necessary pillars, driving them up to their designated block heights, turning off the coupling, and moving to the next line.

