Here is a breakdown of why that alignment logic can get tricky, along with a few ways to bulletproof the sensing array:

1. The Compounding Error Trap
If row 2 aligns itself based only on where it thinks row 1 ended up, and row 3 aligns based on row 2, you create a daisy-chain of measurements.

If a single column has a tiny bit of mechanical play, dust in the threads, or a slight micro-stepping skip, row 1 might be off by just 0.5 mm.

By the time the gantry travels 20 rows down a 40-inch table, those tiny, sub-millimeter fractions can compound (e.g., 0.5 mm×20=10 mm).

