A column rarely goes from absolute zero (0 inches) to full height (12 inches). Instead, it transitions from its previous height to its new height.

If the previous map had a hill at 6 inches high, and the new map turns that spot into a cliff that is 8 inches high, the NEMA 8 motor only needs to turn the all-thread for a 2 inch adjustment.

2-inch adjustment time: At a safe 600 RPM (1 inch per second), that adjustment takes a mere 2 seconds for that row.

2. Streamlining the Reset (Full Down vs. Full Up)
Your insight about the "full down" is mechanically perfect. When resetting the table or changing scenes, you don't need to baby the motors.

The Fast Drop: When columns are moving downward, gravity is working with you instead of against you. The load on the motor drops significantly. You can program a much more aggressive acceleration profile in your software for the "return to home" sweep, cranking the NEMA 8s up to their maximum speed limit (1,200 RPM) to drop the entire row back to zero in a blink.

The Structured Rise: Once a row is cleanly indexed at zero, the lift upward only goes exactly as high as the new map coordinate requires.

Why this works perfectly for D&D
Because the gantry moves row-by-row down the 40-inch table, the physical transition will look like a ripple wave washing across the board. Since most adjacent rows will have similar heights (slight slopes, flat dungeon floors, or small ridges), the carriage will hit its alignment disk, make a series of quick, minor 1-to-3 second adjustments, disengage, and keep rolling.

For your players, it will look less like a tedious "loading screen" and more like the digital fog of war physically rendering the world in real-time right before their eyes.

