Here is how a computer vision tracking loop changes the entire architecture of your project:

1. How the Point Cloud Indexing Loop Works
Instead of the gantry blindly guessing where it is or hunting for magnetic peaks, your software would look like this:

The Scan Phase: The overhead camera captures a 3D depth map of the table surface. Because you are using a clean, Minecraft-style square grid, the software sees a distinct grid of height plateaus and sharp vertical edges.

The Software Alignment (OpenCV / PCL): The code processes the point cloud, aligns it to your digital map layout, and calculates the exact physical millimeter height of every single column.

The Correction Command: If the camera detects that Column (15,8) is sitting at 4.2 inches instead of its intended 4.5 inches, the software calculates the exact delta (+0.3 inches) and tells the gantry row to fix it on the next sweep.

2. The Massive Hardware Wins
By shifting to an overhead sensor, you get a couple of huge mechanical advantages:

True "Zero" Point Homing: You can completely eliminate the 40 limit switches on your traveling carriage. To home the table, you just drop all the columns roughly to the bottom, let the camera look at the surface, and establish the baseline floor visually.

Physical Error Catching: If a player accidentally bumps a terrain block, or a stray dice wedge forces a column down, the overhead camera will instantly spot the deviation on its next frame sweep and tell the gantry to correct the height mid-game.

3. The Big Challenges with Depth Cameras
While the software side is incredibly elegant, there are two real-world physical hurdles to account for with an overhead depth array:

The Miniature Obstruction Problem: If your players have their miniatures, dice, plastic trees, and spell area-of-effect templates sitting on the table, the Kinect will see those shapes as part of the terrain point cloud. Your software will need a filtering algorithm to distinguish between a flat 3D-printed plastic column cap and a plastic Dwarf miniature standing on top of it.

Shadowing/Occlusion: If Row 5 is pushed up to its maximum 12-inch height, and Row 6 is dropped all the way down to 0 inches, a single overhead camera mounted at an angle might experience a "shadow" zone where the tall column completely blocks the camera's line of sight to the short column right behind it. You would need the camera mounted perfectly perpendicular, dead-center above the table, or use a dual-camera setup to eliminate blind spots.

Using an overhead camera to map a dynamic table is incredibly high-tech. It takes the mechanical burden off your physical gantry wiring and hands it over to software processing, which is a fantastic trade-off if you enjoy programming and working with point clouds!

