For a 40×40 inch playing surface, your Y-axis gantry has a significant task: it needs to smoothly carry the weight of 40 NEMA 8 motors, the structural carriage, the sensors, and the docking mechanism down a 40-inch run without racking (one side twisting ahead of the other).

When choosing between Lead Screws and a Rack and Pinion setup for a table of this scale, the engineering trade-offs break down clearly:

Option 1: Rack and Pinion (The Recommended Winner)
For a 40-inch Y-axis travel length, a dual-sided rack and pinion system is highly efficient. You would mount a rigid plastic or steel gear rack along the left and right outer frames of the table.

The Setup: A single NEMA 17 or NEMA 23 motor mounted on the gantry drives a long connecting jack-shaft (a steel rod running across the width of the carriage). This shaft spins two small pinion gears—one on each side—simultaneously engaging both gear racks.

Why it fits your build: * No Whipping: Unlike long screws, gear racks never bow or vibrate at high speeds.

Speed: It will let your gantry sprint back and forth down the 40-inch table between scenes. You can easily clear the entire Y-axis length in under 3 to 4 seconds during a "full down" reset sweep.

Cost: Nylon/plastic gear racks are cheap, rugged, and require zero lubrication, meaning they won't collect stray dust or 3D-printing debris under the table.

Option 2: Lead Screws (Acme / Trapezoidal)
If you went with lead screws for the Y-axis, you would need two long 1000mm T8 lead screws running down the left and right sides of the table frame, driven by two synchronized stepper motors.

The Problem (Screw Whip): A standard 8 mm lead screw spanning 40 inches (over 1 meter) is highly prone to "whipping" (sagging and violently vibrating in the middle) if spun at the high RPMs needed to move the heavy gantry quickly. To prevent this, you would have to buy thick, expensive 12 mm or 16 mm precision screws.

Slow Transit: Because lead screws have high friction and low pitch, driving a heavy 40-motor carriage 40 inches would be slow, adding a lot of dead time to your map transitions.

