Here is how you can optimize the 3D-printed structural components to ensure they hold up to the mechanical forces of the table:

1. Structural Print Settings (No Skimping on Infill)
Since you are printing functional, load-bearing parts (motor mounts, gantry end-plates, and pinion brackets), standard decorative print settings won't cut it.

Material: Use PETG, ABS, or ASA for the motor mounts and gantry plates. Standard PLA can creep (slowly deform under constant mechanical stress or heat from the motors) over time.

Perimeters/Walls: Boost your wall count to at least 4 to 6 perimeters. Wall thickness contributes far more to structural rigidity than infill percentage.

Infill: Use a high-strength geometric pattern like Gyroid or Grid at 40% to 50% infill to absorb motor vibrations.

2. The Floating Motor Mount (The Secrets to Rack Alignments)
Because 3D prints have slight manufacturing tolerances, printing a completely rigid motor mount for the Y-axis gear pinion can sometimes lead to binding if the gear rack isn't perfectly straight.

The Trick: Design a spring-tensioned pivot mount for the Y-axis NEMA 17/23 motor.

By letting the motor mount pivot slightly on a hinge bolt and using a stiff spring to constantly push the pinion gear down into the rack, you guarantee perfect gear engagement with zero backlash, even if the 80/20 frame or printed parts are off by a millimeter.

3. Cable Management (The Drag Chain)
Moving a carriage with 40 individual stepper motors means you have a massive bundle of wires traveling back and forth down the Y-axis.

You can absolutely 3D print a custom drag chain (cable carrier). There are incredible open-source parametric drag chain designs on Printables or Thingiverse that snap together perfectly.

Design Tip: Make sure the internal cavity of the printed drag chain is wide enough to handle the thick wire loom without pinching, and print the links in a low-friction material like PETG so they glide quietly along the table frame.

4. Sourcing Your NEMA 8s
Since you're managing the budget tightly to stay within that $1,000 sweet spot, you can pick up the core components directly. For instance, you can grab standard 1.8° high-torque NEMA 8 Stepper Motors for around $5 to $8 a piece in bulk, keeping your 40-motor row well within the target budget.

