in fair use can we steal the audio track
Under U.S. copyright law, "fair use" is a legal defense, not a blanket permission slip, and it never allows you to simply "steal" or take an entire audio track just because you want to use it.

If you take a copyrighted audio track (like a commercial song or someone else's voiceover) and use it verbatim as the background music for your video, that is almost always considered copyright infringement, not fair use.

To determine if using a portion of an audio track falls under fair use, courts look at Four Factors:

1. The Purpose and Character of the Use
Transformative Use: This is the most critical question. Are you adding something entirely new, or are you just using the track for its original purpose? If you are criticizing, parodying, reviewing, or analyzing the audio track, you have a much stronger claim to fair use.

Derivative Use: If you are just using an epic track as background music to make your own video look cooler, that is not transformative. You are using the music exactly how it was meant to be used, which requires a license.

2. The Nature of the Copyrighted Work
Creative works (like an original song or a musical score) get the highest level of copyright protection. Using a highly creative audio track is much harder to justify under fair use than using a recording of a factual news broadcast or a public speech.

3. The Amount and Substantiality Used
The "Heart" of the Work: There is no "5-second rule" or "10-second rule" in fair use. Even if you only take a tiny snippet of an audio track, if that snippet is the most recognizable hook or the "heart" of the song, it can still weigh heavily against a fair use claim. You should only ever use the absolute bare minimum required to make your point (e.g., a 3-second clip to illustrate a specific mixing technique you are critiquing).

4. The Effect on the Market
Does your video compete with or replace the original audio track? If someone can watch your video and essentially listen to the song or audio track without buying it or streaming it from the original creator, you are harming their market value, which destroys a fair use defense.

How this Applies to YouTube and Content Creation
If you plan to upload a video to YouTube using copyrighted audio, YouTube’s Content ID system does not care about fair use. Content ID is an automated system. If it matches a copyrighted audio track in your video, the copyright owner can automatically claim your ad revenue, mute your video, or block it entirely. To fight this, you would have to file a formal dispute claiming Fair Use, which carries legal risks if the copyright holder decides to issue a formal DMCA takedown notice.

If you are looking for cinematic background music for a project or video, it is always safer and legally bulletproof to use royalty-free music platforms or music licensed under Creative Commons rather than trying to rely on a fair use argument.

